PARAGRAPH.#text: By Geoffrey T. Smith The European Central Bank said Friday it will again accept debt issued, or guaranteed, by the Cypriot government as collateral for its monetary policy operations. The move comes as expected and follows the completion of a debt exchange aimed at lengthening the maturity structure of the country's small stock of publicly-traded government bonds. The exchange was part of the bailout agreement for the island republic that was agreed in February. The ECB's decision follows upgrades from the "Big 3" ratings agencies, signifying that they no longer see the country as in default.

Headlines.Headline: Demand For ECB's Weekly Credit Operation Falls

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Geoffrey T. Smith Demand at the European Central Bank's regular weekly offer of liquidity fell Tuesday, with banks requiring only 107.70 billion euros ($140.09 billion) to satisfy their needs, down from EUR117.31 billion a week earlier. The ECB said its Main Refinancing Operation, which has been offered at a fixed rate of 0.50% since early May, attracted bids from 78 banks. That is also down from 99 banks last week. As such, both the volume and the number of bidders are comfortably back in the range that has prevailed for most of the last two months, after a spike in demand last week that appeared to be caused by volatility in global markets.

"We have heard...that a range of precautionary measures has been taken," Andreas Vosskuhle, the president of the Federal Constitutional Court, said in a reference to testimony given Tuesday by ECB board member Joerg Asmussen.

Headlines.Author: Geoffrey T. Smith
Headlines.Headline: ECB's Mersch: OMT Needs Controlled Uncertainty To Keep Its Edge-Report

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Geoffrey T. Smith The European Central Bank needs to be able to play its hand freely and not show all its cards at once if ever it buys the bonds of stressed euro-zone governments, board member Yves Mersch told the German newspaper Boersen-Zeitung Tuesday. "In order to convince the markets, a degree of 'controlled uncertainty is necessary," Mr. Mersch was quoted as saying. He stressed that the ECB's desire not to announce pre-set limits to its interventions does not mean that there will literally be no end to its purchases.
